abstract={Often lossless jet noise data obtained by various researchers in different facilities does not match after allowing for jet operating conditions, measurement distance, and nozzle dimensions using accepted jet noise scaling laws. There have been a number of explanations for these differences, but the most contentious of these is attributing rig-noise contamination to be the cause of the difference. This calls all the measurements that have been acquired in the facility into question. Knowing if jet noise is contaminated by rig-noise in a given facility is crucial to obtaining high-quality jet noise data and a simple method is needed to determine if rig-noise is indeed present in a given set of measurements. One such method is the so-called Doubling-Diameter Method first published by the second author. Verification of this method is the focus of the present study. This verification was conducted using cylindrical obstructions upstream of the nozzle-exit. Not only was it shown that this method can accurately detect rig-noise contamination, but in a case study the GTRI Anechoic Jet-Facility was shown to be free of rig-noise contamination. © 2017, American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics Inc, AIAA. All rights reserved.},
